<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
A. Options Considered for the Presumptive Limit 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Our primary goal in setting limits for coordinated care organizations is to ensure that we do not pay more for Medicare
beneficiaries enrolled in these organizations than we would pay if the beneficiaries were not so enrolled. The AAPCC
is an estimate of the average per capita cost for Medicare beneficiaries who receive their Medicare-covered services
in the fee-for-service sector, that is, Medicare beneficiaries who are not enrolled in HMOs, CMPs, or HCPPs. Because
it is a per capita estimate based on 100% of the costs for these beneficiaries in a geographic area, we consider it to
be an excellent basis for estimating the aggregate amount that HCFA would have paid for HMO, CMP, and HCPP enrollees
if they had not been so enrolled. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
HCFA has used the AAPCC in connection with cost limits or other controls for prepaid health care organizations as follows:

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
1. Before 1985, under a demonstration, as the basis for payment to risk HMOs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
